[2026-07-10] [Ask My Docs / Audience] — Decision: Portfolio piece for hiring managers/potential clients. Rejected: personal-use-only framing. Because: seed spec's "portfolio-grade README" language and user confirmation both point to presentation-quality deliverables, not just a working demo.
[2026-07-10] [Ask My Docs / Dense embeddings] — Decision: `sentence-transformers` with `bge-small-en-v1.5`, benchmark against `fastembed` on actual dev hardware before finalizing. Rejected: committing to `fastembed` on reputation alone. Because: research surfaced multiple reports of `fastembed` being slower than sentence-transformers on CPU for MiniLM-class models — the "fast" branding isn't a reliable signal on CPU specifically.
[2026-07-10] [Ask My Docs / Vector store] — Decision: `lancedb`. Rejected: `chromadb` (not meant for production/p99-sensitive scale), raw `faiss-cpu` (no persistence or metadata filtering). Because: embedded (no server), scales past RAM via disk-based indexing, built-in hybrid search + reranking support.
[2026-07-10] [Ask My Docs / Reranker] — Decision: `cross-encoder/ms-marco-MiniLM-L-6-v2` as default, `bge-reranker-base` as config-swappable alternative. Rejected: hardcoding a single reranker. Because: both measure ~130ms/16-candidate batch on CPU; MiniLM-L6-v2 is the standard speed/quality default, and candidate/rerank counts are already config-driven so the model choice should be too.
[2026-07-10] [Ask My Docs / Tracing] — Decision: Langfuse cloud free tier (Hobby) first, self-host via Docker later if needed. Rejected: self-hosting from day one. Because: cloud tier is simpler to stand up on a single Windows dev machine; the tracer sits behind an interface so switching later needs no pipeline code changes.
[2026-07-10] [Ask My Docs / Ingestion library] — Decision: `pymupdf` over `pdftotext`/plain extraction for the actual ingestion pipeline. Rejected: pure regex-based heading detection on plain text. Because: real PDF inspection showed chapter headers are regex-detectable but subsection headers are not — font-size/bold metadata (which pymupdf exposes and pdftotext discards) is required for reliable heading detection.
[2026-07-10] [Ask My Docs / Cost control] — Decision: add a local response cache (keyed on question + config hash) for the eval harness, and a daily running cost total (not just per-request) surfaced from Langfuse. Rejected: relying on per-request cost visibility alone. Because: eval-harness debugging re-spends identically on unchanged inputs without a cache, and per-request cost doesn't surface aggregate runaway the way a daily total does.
[2026-07-10] [Ask My Docs / Chunking] — Decision: subsection-boundary-first chunking (via pymupdf font metadata) with ~400-600 token sliding-window fallback and ~15% overlap for long subsections; chunk ID = deterministic hash of (chapter, section_title, sequence). Rejected: fixed-size sliding window only; row-index-based chunk IDs. Because: some subsections span 8+ pages (would fragment a maneuver's procedure if purely fixed-size), and row-index IDs break on re-ingestion after wording tweaks, invalidating golden eval references.
[2026-07-11] [Ask My Docs / Environment] — Decision: use `uv` for Python version + dependency management (`pyproject.toml` + `uv.lock`), not `pip`/`venv`/`requirements.txt`. Rejected: assuming a system Python install per the original repo-structure sketch. Because: this machine has no system Python at all (only Windows Store stub aliases), but `uv` was already installed and already had Python 3.11.8 provisioned — zero-friction path to the "Python 3.11+" requirement.
[2026-07-11] [Ask My Docs / Chunking] — Decision: add `tiktoken` (cl100k_base) as the token-counting utility for the chunker's 400-600 token sizing, config-driven, CPU-only. Rejected: word-count as a token proxy. Because: the design doc specifies chunk size in tokens, and word count is not an accurate proxy; tiktoken is offline after first encoding download, no GPU, negligible footprint.
[2026-07-11] [Ask My Docs / Testing] — Decision: ingestion unit tests build synthetic PDFs in-memory via PyMuPDF's own `fitz.open()`/`insert_text(fontname=...)` API (built-in "helv"/"hebo" fonts control the bold flag), never depend on the real 273MB handbook. Rejected: checked-in binary PDF fixtures. Because: keeps tests fast, deterministic, and reviewable as plain Python; the real handbook is gitignored and only used for the manual Chunk 1.14 spot-check.
[2026-07-11] [Ask My Docs / Plan scope] — Decision (user call): `/plan` output gives full TDD chunk detail only for Block 0 (env/config) and Block 1 (ingestion); Blocks 2-9 sketched at block-level, detailed via a follow-up `/plan` once Block 1's real chunk data/schemas exist. Rejected: full-detail TDD steps for all ~9 blocks in one pass. Because: later blocks' test design depends on ingestion's actual output shapes, which aren't known yet — writing exact test code now would be designing against guesses.
[2026-07-11] [Ask My Docs / Chunking] — Decision confirmed at build time: `tiktoken` (cl100k_base encoding) is the token counter used by `src/ingest/tokens.py:count_tokens` for chunk-size gating. Rejected: word-count proxy. Because: chunk size is specified in tokens (400-600) in the design doc; tiktoken downloads its encoding file once (verified working in this environment) then runs fully offline/CPU-only.
[2026-07-11] [Ask My Docs / Ingestion] — Decision: subsection headers must be the sole content of their PDF line (new `line_span_count` field on `TextSpan`), not bold-or-larger-font alone. Rejected: bold-only heuristic as originally planned. Because: real-corpus spot-check (Chunk 1.14) showed the FAA handbook bolds inline field labels mid-sentence ("Rule #1:", "Throttle:"), which the original heuristic misclassified as headers, fragmenting 60% of chunks to under 50 tokens (target 400-600). Fixed via TDD on a synthetic fixture reproducing the failure; re-ingestion measured 1,850 -> 1,008 chunks, median token count 29 -> 173.5.
[2026-07-11] [Ask My Docs / Ingestion] — Deferred (logged to BUGS.md, not fixed): sliding-window fallback sizes windows by word count as a token-count proxy, confirmed to undercount badly on numeral-dense TOC/Glossary/Index text (a 600-word real chunk measured 1,275 actual tokens). Rejected: patching this in the same session as the header-line fix. Because: it's a distinct root cause from the header bug and deserves its own TDD cycle against `count_tokens`, not a quick tweak layered onto an already-large spot-check session.
[2026-07-11] [Ask My Docs / Ingestion] — Open question, not decided: should front/back-matter (Table of Contents, Glossary, Index) be filtered out of the retrieval corpus entirely, given they chunk into near-empty, low-retrieval-value fragments? Deferred to Block 2/6 once real retrieval-quality signal exists to inform the call, rather than guessing now.
[2026-07-11] [Ask My Docs / Retrieval] — Decision confirmed at build time (Chunk 2.3 real-corpus spot-check): config fusion weights are load-bearing end-to-end — flipping bm25_weight/vector_weight (5.0/0.1 vs 0.1/5.0) visibly reorders top-5 results on the real handbook indexes, including the #1 result for the VMC/VSO and crosswind sample queries. This satisfies the design doc's "switching fusion weights via config visibly changes retrieval" acceptance criterion.
[2026-07-11] [Ask My Docs / Retrieval] — Finding, not a decision (logged to BUGS.md): the Chunk 2.3 spot-check produced the first real retrieval-quality signal on the two deferred ingestion questions. (1) Front/back-matter pollution is real: index/page-number-list chunks rank in the top-5 for 2 of 3 sample queries, once as the #1 vector-heavy result. (2) New finding: V-speed subscripts ("V" + "MC"/"SO" spans) are split by extraction, so no chunk defining VMC/VSO surfaced for the V-speed sample query under any weighting. Both deferred to ingestion-side fixes before Block 6 evals, not patched in Block 2 — retrieval is behaving correctly over the corpus it was given.
[2026-07-12] [Ask My Docs / Ingestion] — Decision: join subscript spans to their base span geometrically (<0.8x font size, <=1pt x-gap, top edge below base) in pdf_loader, because PyMuPDF does NOT set its superscript flag on the handbook's V-speed subscripts — verified against real span data before writing the fix. Rejected: flag-based detection (flag never set); tokenizer-side normalization (would leave citations/chunk text showing "V MC"). Result: "VMC"/"VSO" survive extraction intact (62 spans contain "VMC", was 0).
[2026-07-12] [Ask My Docs / Ingestion] — Decision (resolves the open front/back-matter question): filter spans to a config-driven body page range (chunking.body_page_start/body_page_end, 0-based inclusive; 21-390 for FAA-H-8083-3C) BEFORE header detection. Glossary (372-390) kept — real definitional content that serves eval questions (a glossary V-speed chunk surfaces for the VMC/VSO query); front matter/TOC (0-20) and Index (391-405) dropped. Rejected: filtering chunks after chunking (leaves TOC's verbatim "Chapter N:" lines duplicating every chapter header and index headings fragmenting sections); heuristic landmark detection (more machinery than a two-value config for a single-corpus project). Rebuilt corpus: 951 -> 617 chunks, median tokens 173.5 -> 329, sub-50-token share 33% -> 8%.
[2026-07-13] [Ask My Docs / Retrieval] — Decision: reciprocal_rank_fusion raises ValueError on rankings/weights length mismatch (zip strict=True). Rejected: silent zip truncation (the previous behavior). Because: a mis-sized weights config would silently degrade hybrid retrieval to single-index retrieval with no error — exactly the silent-failure class this project exists to catch. Found by /audit's fresh-eyes review; none of Block 2's four fusion tests probed the input contract.
[2026-07-13] [Ask My Docs / Rerank] — Decision: rerank() takes candidates as (chunk_id, text) pairs, not parallel id/text lists. Rejected: parallel lists with a strict-zip guard. Because: pairs make length mismatch unrepresentable — the bug class the RRF zip fix guarded against at runtime is excluded structurally here.
[2026-07-13] [Ask My Docs / Rerank] — Decision: enabled=False still truncates to top_k (passthrough for order only). Rejected: byte-pure passthrough returning all top_n candidates. Because: downstream consumers get "at most top_k chunks" as a stable function contract regardless of the config toggle — a generation prompt sized for 5 chunks must not receive 20 because someone A/B'd the reranker.
[2026-07-13] [Ask My Docs / Ingest] — Decision: get_chunk_texts raises KeyError on missing ids, applies no scan limit, and SQL-escapes ids in the filter string. Rejected: returning partial results (silent degradation — would have hidden both the limit bug and the duplicate-id corpus bug); a limit sized to len(ids) (added as untested "insurance", it truncated the scan when duplicate ids inflated the match count — removed via TDD).
[2026-07-13] [Ask My Docs / Ingestion] — Finding (HIGH, logged to BUGS.md, not fixed this session): make_chunk_id(chapter, section_title, sequence) collides on repeated section titles — real corpus has 617 rows / 590 unique ids, one id shared by 5 different "Common errors" chunks. Must add a hash disambiguator (page_index_start or per-chapter occurrence index) and re-ingest before Block 5 citations / Block 6 golden dataset.
[2026-07-13] [Ask My Docs / Rerank] — Finding (logged to BUGS.md): rerank latency is ~5.3s per 20 real-length candidates on CPU vs the design doc's ~130ms/16 claim, which holds only for short passages (probe on toy strings measured 63ms/16 — production-shaped inputs are now a /build probe requirement). Chunks >512 tokens are silently truncated by the cross-encoder during scoring. Mitigation decision deferred to Block 4 (reduce top_n, cap max_length, or accept for CLI).
[2026-07-13] [Ask My Docs / Ingestion] — Decision: chunk-id disambiguator is page_index_start, not a per-chapter occurrence counter. Rejected: occurrence index (shifts for all later same-title sections whenever header detection changes earlier in the chapter — worse citation stability under chunker evolution); dropping content-hash ids for UUIDs (breaks re-ingestion stability entirely). Also: chunk_pdf now counts the uniqueness invariant and raises on collisions — designed invariants get verified at the point they're produced, per the kaizen rule.
[2026-07-13] [Ask My Docs / Ingestion] — Decision: group_into_sections matches header spans by (title, font_size, is_bold) per page, not text equality. Because: the ingest-time collision check fired on the real corpus — glossary V-speed notation leaves stray standalone letter spans whose text equals the page's alphabet heading ("V" x5 on p388), spawning bogus sections; font signature distinguishes them (stray spans are body-sized). Rejected: adding bbox to SubsectionHeader for true span identity (schema churn not needed until font-signature matching demonstrably fails).
[2026-07-13] [Ask My Docs / Process] — Decision (/kaizen): audit.md's Technical Audit checklist rewritten stack-native (uv/pytest/index-rebuild/contract/comment-integrity checks) replacing an inherited npm/Vitest/Supabase/React checklist and a pointer to a nonexistent .agent/REFERENCE.md; build.md gains a mandatory contract-RED-test step and a config-isolation rule for corpus-specific config keys. Rejected: keeping the generic template checks and mentally filtering per audit. Because: two consecutive audits caught silent-contract bugs happy-path TDD missed (dead min_tokens param; RRF zip truncation), and a false comment survived a full audit cycle — the checklist should encode what this repo actually fails at.
[2026-07-13] [Ask My Docs / Generation] — Decision (/plan Block 4): fix stale GenerationConfig.model default from claude-sonnet-4-5 to claude-sonnet-5. Because: claude-sonnet-4-5 predates the current model catalog; the config already carried a "verify at build time" comment flagging this. Rejected: leaving it, since the design doc's own audience (hiring managers reviewing a portfolio piece) would read an outdated model string as neglect.
[2026-07-13] [Ask My Docs / Generation] — Decision (/plan Block 4): use client.messages.parse(output_format=GeneratedAnswer) for structured citation output; SDK-native client.with_options(max_retries=, timeout=) for retry/timeout instead of hand-rolled backoff. Rejected: hand-written JSON parsing (structured outputs make the shape unrepresentable-as-wrong, same design principle as Block 3's (id,text) pairs); a config-driven backoff_base_seconds (the SDK already does exponential backoff on 429/5xx, so a custom base delay would be dead configuration nobody exercises).
[2026-07-13] [Ask My Docs / Generation] — Decision (/plan Block 4): explicitly set thinking={"type": "disabled"} for answer generation. Because: claude-sonnet-5 runs adaptive thinking by default when the field is omitted, and a short extraction-and-cite task doesn't need multi-step reasoning — every skipped thinking token is a real cost saving over the eval harness's lifetime, consistent with the project's daily-cost-cap design pillar.
[2026-07-13] [Ask My Docs / Generation] — Decision (/plan Block 4): answer_question orchestrator reuses one get_chunk_texts fetch for both rerank's top-n candidates and generation's top-k prompt (rerank's output ids are a subset of its input ids). Rejected: a second get_chunk_texts call after rerank (resolves the Block 3 debt note without touching rerank's already-shipped contract); changing rerank to return (id, text) pairs (unnecessary churn on tested code for no behavioral gain).
[2026-07-13] [Ask My Docs / Testing] — Decision (/plan Block 4): add a live_api pytest marker (skipped unless RUN_LIVE_API_TESTS=1) for the first tests that call the real, paid Anthropic API. Because: Block 1's plan explicitly deferred this "Live-Service Test Gate" to whichever block first needed it; Block 4 is that block.
[2026-07-14] [Ask My Docs / Citations] — Decision (/plan Block 5, user choice): faithfulness verification is a Haiku LLM-judge, batched into one structured-output call per answer (list[CitationVerdict]), not one call per citation and not a local NLI cross-encoder or reused rerank score. Because: the user picked the LLM-judge over the two zero-cost alternatives (Recommended option) for its ability to catch nuanced unsupported claims, consistent with this project's existing "haiku for judges" stack decision; batching keeps latency to one round-trip regardless of citation count instead of N sequential calls.
[2026-07-14] [Ask My Docs / Citations] — Decision (/plan Block 5): citations.judge_model/judge_temperature are new CitationConfig fields, kept separate from eval.judge_model/judge_temperature despite an identical default value. Because: eval's judge grades golden-dataset answers in Block 6's batch harness; citations' judge fires on every live query to check faithfulness — different call sites likely to need independent tuning. Rejected: unifying into one shared judge config now, before either call site has evidence it needs to diverge.
