[2026-07-14] [Ask My Docs / Eval] — Decision (/plan Block 6, user choice): the answer-quality judge scores two independent boolean dimensions, correct and complete, not a single combined score. Because: completeness is a new metric that directly targets the already-logged Block 4 gap (question 3, short-field vs. soft-field takeoff, answered only half the comparison) — correctness alone would not flag a half-answer as a failure. Rejected: correctness-only (misses the known gap); correctness+completeness+groundedness (redundant with citations.coverage, already computed on every live query by Block 5).
[2026-07-14] [Ask My Docs / Eval] — Finding (HIGH), not a decision: Block 6's first real end-to-end run caught generation (Block 4) fabricating an 8-item "According to the handbook" errors list for q4 (crosswind takeoff) that isn't present in its single cited chunk or anywhere in the corpus. Block 5's citation verification does not catch this class of failure -- the cited chunk is genuinely relevant by verify_citations' own per-citation definition, so the fabrication is in unverified prose, not an unsupported citation. Matches Block 5's own stated scope limitation (Decision 6: citations-only, not full prose faithfulness) manifesting as a concrete instance on the very first opportunity. Not fixed this session; logged to BUGS.md as HIGH.
[2026-07-14] [Ask My Docs / Eval] — Finding, not a decision: q1 (VMC vs VSO) scored correct=True on the first real eval run and correct=False on an immediate re-run of the identical question, with genuinely different generated content each time. GenerationConfig has no temperature field (defaults to the Anthropic SDK's default), so this is real generation non-determinism, not retrieval/rerank variance as previously assumed for the Q3 gap. Concrete evidence for the design doc's tolerance-band (not hard-cutoff) CI comparison choice. Motivates a future decision on whether generation.temperature should be pinned low for reproducibility; not decided this session.
